<br>
1. Over estimate your requirements.<br>
        Never get a cooling fan that goes up to the processor your using. Never get a power supply that is the base requirement. Never buy a motherboard that will work up to the processor your using. ALWAYS overestimate. If your using a 2.5 Ghz CPU, then get a fan that will cool a 3.2 Ghz or faster. Never get a 350 Watt power supply. Always get a 450 or higher. Anything less and your limiting your upgrade options. And make sure you buy a motherboard that goes above and beyond the call of duty. If your getting a 2.5Ghz processor, get a motherboard that will support a MUCH faster processor. All of these leave you room for cheap, and substantial upgrades in the future, as opposed to trashing and building a new one.<br>
<br>
2. Only buy name brand RAM.<br>
       Generic RAM is rampant all over the net these days. Most of these generic type RAM modules are either overclocked RAM, or substandard quality. Buy only names like Crucial, Kingston, GEIL, Viking, Corsair, OCZ, or other name brand modules. These companies make higher quality, longer lasting, and overall better performing RAM. Anything less, and you'll be complaining about bottlenecks, crashes, lag, lock ups, and a bundle of other problems. RAM is never an area to save money.<br>
<br>
3. CPU brand doesn't matter.<br>
       No matter what the fan-boys fling at you, CPU brand doesn't matter. No matter what anyone says, it usually boils down to: Intel = High Price/High Performance AMD = Low Price/90% the performance of an equal intel. There are many ups and downs to each, and fanboys from each side whine they're pros, but each have they're place in the market. Both will play modern games to max performance and both are majorly supported by game manufacturers. By having either one will never give you an advantage over the other. Intels generally run 10% faster, and run 30% cooler, but are twice to three times the price. AMDs run at 90% of an intel, run a good bit hotter than intels, but are MUCH cheaper. No matter which one you buy, you wont be dissapointed.<br>
<br>
4. NEVER BUY A BUDGET GAME CARD<br>
       Budget cards are crap. Yea, they might play games that are coming out right now, but in 6 months, your going to be whining about having to get a new card. Never buy the fastest of fast either. Top end cards are just as much a waste of money as buying a budget card. Most high end cards only give a 20% - 30% speed boost, at 150 - 200% the price. Now if your looking at getting a multimedia card, like the All-in-Wonder or Personal Cinema cards, then ya might want to get a upper end card, since the addition of the multimedia aspects, usually call for a lowering of graphics power, due to the cause of heat restrictions, and power consumption. So unless you have more money than ya know what to do with, go for a mid level card. The ATI 9600 Pro or the Nvidia 5600 Pro are both great bang for buck cards. <br>
<br>
4. Never buy a budget motherboard.<br>
     First of all, avoid anything with a SiS chipset on it. Also, avoid anything with built in video. Even with the built in video disabled, it can cause performance drops. Also avoid PC CHIPS, ALBATRON, and ALSROCK. The boards are designed to work. Nothing more. If your building someone a computer to type up reports and surf the internet, they're fine. But for gaming, they suck. Majorly. Also, get a motherboard with the fastest chipset available. These boards give you increased functionality, and multiple new speed increasing options. A motherboard is another area you should never cheapen off on. A good board usually never cost less than $100. The best boards usually are in the $125 - $150 range.<br>
<br>
5. High end sound cards sometimes are not worth the money.<br>
      Sure, having a nice 8 channel $100 - $200 sound card seems nice, but if all your doing is playing EQ and the occasional FPS, then having a Audigy 2 Platinum EX might be somewhat of an overkill. The only people I usually reccomend high end sound cards to are people who are going to use they're computers as media stations. If your going to be watching DVDs, using your computer as your radio and jukebox, or creating music on your PC, then a high end card might be the better choice for you. High end cards usually take a 20% - 30% performance chunk out of your system. Also, most of the effects that high end cards provide are never noticed unless you have a $250 or higher priced speakers. Since 99% of motherboards these days have built in sound cards, for the average gamer, these are more than enough. They usually support 5.1 and 6.1 sound, and are usually supported by all games. Also, since most built in sound cards are standardized, driver support is much more common. Creative, and most of the other high end sound card providers have a tough time with driver support with the newest games due to the seemingly infinate number of combination of computers. So, unless you really want to spend the money, you might want to just stick with a built in sound card. High end ones are nice, but you will soon discover how rarely you use the extra functions. Your choice here.<br>
<br>
6. BUY A GOOD CASE!!<br>
      A poorly designed case can seriously be a thorn in the flesh for a gaming PC. A well designed case should be sturdy, well ventilated, plently of open space, and easy to work on. My personal favorite is the Chieftec DX series (Shown Below)<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://images10.newegg.com/productimage/11-125-264-09.JPG" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
These cases are VERY well designed and very well ventilated. I use these in all the systems I build. They are cheap, and more than adequate for gaming. Just throw in a 450 Watt power supply, a few fans, and your choice of components and your ready to game. Having front USB and Firewire ports just adds to the enjoyment. Use the case of your choice, just try to inspect a case first. Check local stores for case displays. Besy Buy usually has some cases on display, as with most local computer stores.<br>
<br>
7. Buy CDROMS(Burners), Keyboards, Mice, Monitors, UPSs, and Mice locally.<br>
       CD Drives, Keyboards, Mice, and other compents can usually bought very cheap locally (Sometimes free with rebates) and you dont have to pay shipping and returns are MUCH easier. Monitors and UPSs should be bought locally because of weight. These items usually cause shipping to skyrocket, and monitors can easily get damaged unless you pay for enhanced shipping.<br>
<br>
8. Try to purchase all your items at the same site.<br>
      Wether it's www.newegg.com, www.mwave.com, www.buyxg.com, or www.directron.com, try to buy all your items at one place. This makes RMAs (returns) much easier, and you dont have to keep up with a world of paperwork. Also, some sites offer discounts for bundled components. If you have a system in mind to build, add all the items into the shopping cart on all the sites, and find out who gives the cheaper package AFTER shipping rates. Some companies will lower prices, and jack up shipping to compensate for the loss. Crooked, so avoid these sites like the plague.<br>
<br>
9.USE A STATIC STRAP!!!<br>
    If you are going to build a system, go to Radioshack, or any electronics store and buy a static strap. You might be able to build a system without it, but if you have an ESD (Electrostatic Discharge) on a Video Card, RAM, CPU, Motherboard, or any other fragile piece of hardware, you'll be out a ton of money. It could have been avoided if you had a 6 dollar static strap. They're annoying yes, but the odds of you having a mistake far outweigh the annoyance.<br>
<br>
10. CPU and MEMORY speeds should ALWAYS be sync'd.<br>
       A 266Mhz FSB CPU should have DDR 2100 (266Mhz) RAM or a 333Mhz FSB CPU should have DDR 2700 (333Mhz) RAM. Anything faster or slower will cause bottlenecks, either the RAM waiting on the CPU, not letting DATA move in the RAM till the CPU catches up, and the CPU waiting on RAM. Either one will piss ya off when gaming gets tense. Try to keep your CPU FSB and RAM speed the same. You wont regret it.<br>
<br>
If you go by these guidlines, you can have a massive gaming system that wont drain your wallet, will last a long time, and will be a cinch to upgrade later down the road. Never buy a name brand system if you can help it. Even the name brand &quot;gaming&quot; systems cut corners terribly on cooling and power consumption. Alienware computers are nice, and are a nice alternative to building, if you have the money to afford one. But also remember that you can have a system ten times better for the money you'd sink into one Alienware computer. Your buying a name and a fancy looking case more than anything. Computers are insanely easy to build these days, any moron can build one. And as soon as you build your first one, your going to be pissed ya never did before. If you need more help or information, just send me an ezboard email thing and I'll respond ASAP. As bad as name brand computer companies rip off consumers these days, I wish everyone built they're own computers. I'll be more than glad to help ya dude. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bryannaesalvasti>Bryannae Salvasti</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I'm not a cleric!<br>
